IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: Hamline University is a nationally ranked comprehensive university serving 4,500 students in its College of Liberal Arts, School of Education, and School of Business. It offers undergraduate, masters, doctorate and professional degrees, as well as certificate and continuing studies programs.
IRS990.MissionDesc: The mission of the university is to create a diverse and collaborative community of learning dedicated to the development of students' knowledge, values and skills for successful lives of leadership, scholarship and service.
IRS990.Desc: Hamline University is a nationally-ranked, comprehensive university serving nearly 4,500 students in its College of Liberal Arts, School of Education, and School of Business. It offers undergraduate, masters, doctoral and professional degrees, as well as certificate and continuing studies programs. Founded in 1854, Hamline University was the first institution of higher learning in Minnesota. The University has established a national reputation for academic quality, as well as providing students with personal attention and exceptional experiences. Hamline is one of just 283 Phi Beta Kappa institutions in the United States. Among comprehensive universities, U.S. News and World Report ranks Hamline in the top two in Minnesota in its category of Best Regional Universities. Hamline is ranked twenty-second in the nation by Washington Monthly's College Rankings of service-oriented schools.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: Hamline University provides academic support to its students through support services that are an integral part of the University's primary mission of instruction. This includes expenses for libraries, galleries, audio/visual services, academic development, academic computing support, course and curriculum development, and academic administration.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: Hamline University provides student services to its students and includes such expenses as admissions, financial aid administration, registrar activities, and activities that contribute to students' emotional and physical well-being and to their intellectual, cultural, and social development outside the context of the formal instructional program.

ProgSrvcAccomActyOtherGrp.Desc: Hamline University provides auxiliary services to students which are essentially the self-supporting operations of the University. These services charge a fee to students that is directly related to, although not necessarily equal to, the cost of providing the service. Examples are residence halls, food services, student health services, and the campus bookstore.

Hamline University provides other program services by way of other offices and activities to support the program activities of the University. Expenses in this area include research expenses related to activities specifically organized to produce research outcomes, either commissioned by an agency external to the institution or separately budgeted by an organizational unit within the University. Expenses also include public service expenses related specifically to public service and for activities established primarily to provide non-instructional services beneficial to groups external to the institution. This includes expenses for the Wesley Center.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The University is a member of Minnesota Private College Council (MPCC), an organization described in section 501(c)(4) of the Internal Revenue Code. MPCC is an association of private nonprofit institutions of higher education that serves a variety of its members' shared needs, including, but not only, nonpartisan and non-electoral advocacy for public policy that meets students' needs and advances the interests of private higher education. The University paid membership dues to MPCC in the amount of $141,522 during the taxable year. MPCC has divided its expenses for its taxable year ending June 30, 2017, into two groups. Group 1 consists of those expenses that did not in any way support attempts to influence legislation within the meaning of section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code ("lobbying"), and Group 2 consists of all other expenses. Group 2 includes many expenses, such as personnel costs, that supported both lobbying and non-lobbying activities. MPCC did not attempt to allocate the Group 2 expenses between lobbying and non-lobbying activities. MPCC has determined that the amount of the Group 2 expenses represents 78.81% of the amount of the dues that MPCC collected in the same taxable year. Assuming that all Group 2 expenses were paid from member dues, and allocating those expenses pro rata based on the dues paid by each member, $111,536 of the University's dues were used to pay Group 2 expenses. The amount of lobbying expenses paid from the University's dues was significantly less than that amount.

The University's collections, which were acquired through purchases and contributions since the University's inception, are not recognized as assets on the balance sheet. Purchases of collection items are recorded as decreases in unrestricted net assets in the year in which the items are acquired or as temporarily restricted net assets if the assets that are used to purchase the items are restricted by the donors. Contributed collection items are not reflected on the financial statements. Proceeds from de-accessions or insurance recoveries are reflected as increases in the appropriate net asset classes.

The University's collection is made up of pottery, prints, musical instruments and paintings that are held for educational and performance purposes. Each of the items is catalogued, preserved and cared for and activities verifying their existence and assessing their condition are performed continuously.

The intended uses of the endowment funds are to establish a scholarship or prize, to create a chair in a specific academic area, to fund a particular research program, to fund other programs such as professorships, fellowships, library, buildings, equipment and lectures and discretionary use by the University (unrestricted).
